00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And we wanted to play in it, didn't know the seriousness of it, like just what happened, you know.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
But to the, and where the water was running, that's where the crop screw.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
I mean, cotton go right up to the house, you can go out the window, go to work right there.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Everything's right there.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And remember when we lived there, we lived next door to my grandmother.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
There's like a food orchard between and we lived next door in the shotgun house, brand new shotgun house.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.000
We lived in, and the next to us was a sawmill, actually experienced lumber being made.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Bringing these big logs in, and man, this big saw, it would be screaming, you know, cutting that wood.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So it was right there with the congregation of a clump of people right there.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
And other than that, you just got cotton fields.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:23.000
Not much in terms of corn, edible, vegetable, cotton was the main thing.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.000
We had a train that ran not too far away.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:36.000
We had a church right nearby where I started school, one room, one teacher taught everybody.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
And she had much order.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
I remember once my uncle made the teacher kind of angry.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And he told us she laughed like a duck.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
So she had him to go out and bring some switches in.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And I was terrified.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
This lady's going, kill us, you know, back then.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
She was open, just open to be had, you know.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
So she had no trouble, I was only about seven years old.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And of course, the next year went up town.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Our lab becomes up town.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
It's still very rural and very country.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And I went to school up there where we did have classrooms.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So it was a very wonderful experience.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
And I remember the cemetery was right by the church.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
I understand now because they didn't have anything to take anywhere.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So they buried you right outside the church.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Same place they had planned.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
They had dug a grave for him at the till.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So that's what I remember.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And some people live back down in the woods like.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
They were all surrounded by a farm there.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
Everything is farming.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Few settlements, but everything related to the farming.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And up town we had three or four stores,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
whatever, very few stores.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
And that was the extent of it.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
You didn't know anything about fast food,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
so they had to cook three times a day.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:56.000
I mean, you had to eat.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
You could not go into the cotton field with no cornflakes.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
We never heard of cornflakes in cold series.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
Like, you had to eat some rabbit, some chicken,

