There's a whole lot of conglomeration of things coming together. You got players, you got, which is not mentioned much, Alvin Sykes.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:34.000
You don't hear much about Alvin. Alvin played a pivotal role. And sometimes what I saw I didn't like because some people act like they own a story.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:39.000
I say stupid, stupidity. I mean, it's a story that's out there, you know.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:49.000
And Alvin Sykes was a one that really, (Alvin Sykes) came here with specific one reason to get it open because he had done a case out there in Kansas.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:50:03.000
And so he pursued and I went with Alvin and we met with Eric Holder. And Eric Holder felt it referred to him as a legend in his own time.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:12.000
He pursued, he was a kid, I don't think he had a high school education, but he's well-trenched in the language.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:33.000
And I guess he studied it over and over and he pursued these sentences about the Till Bill. And then they got (George W.) (George W.) Bush signed a TL bill that allowed $11 million a year for 10 years to be put toward pursuing cases dating back from 1970.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:43.000
Then he pursued the appropriations [for the Till Bill]. I thought once the bill was passed, the money's automatic. I didn't know you got anything. So he pursued that.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:53.000
I have a lot of respect for Alvin, a lot of respect for him. And he's so unpretentious. That's what I like about. You're not eagle just.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And you know, it's not, whoever gets the credit, you know, he don't worry about this. So I've been on a million times to support him. So that's what it was like.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:28.000
Let's get talking a little more about what you, your thoughts on your perspective as the case was reopened by Justice Department and officials in Mississippi and how you looked at that process, what range of motions and feelings that provoked in your sense of how that was handled.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:41.000
The case was reopened to 2005. I'm interested in your range of thoughts about that as you watched the things that did happen in that process, including the explanation of the body.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:51.000
Ultimately decision down by Mississippi officials and others not to move forward with any new indictment.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:57.000
The range of emotion you felt, the range of opinion you had about how all that was handled.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:12.000
When the first term of that was going to be open, I had a pessimistic view or a negative view. I say, no, we anywhere, all the white men in Mississippi, I open this case, you know what I mean? That's my first thought.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:25.000
Then it's a well as a woman. I said, maybe you wait a moment. Then it says a black woman, I'll leave you with this child. I said, well, maybe you know, it'll be open.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:38.000
I was concerned about her, knowing Mississippi, knowing people that you can't legislate the heart, I was concerned about that with one of my concerns.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:52.000
And how else did I feel? So they gave her the FBI did something that they wouldn't do about 50 years ago. They did the investigation.

00:52:52.000 --> 00:53:02.000
I never expected a whole lot because I know that attitude, atmosphere of the country. I know where I'm at. I'm a realist.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:12.000
I never expected a whole awful lot happening quick, but you know, I know that animosity is going to be still here.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:23.000
I don't expect no jumping in the bed type thing to happen. Okay. So they gave her an information. I made with the FBI. We did all this stuff.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:38.000
This is more progress than we ever made. So you appreciate that. We respect that. Now we got the FBI literally and they asked in court and seemed like they maybe kind of serious about getting to the bottom of us.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:48.000
So she gave it to the grand jury. She grand jury came back to say, FBI thought they had enough information to indict someone.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:54:00.000
I'm not interested in anyone getting the data. I'm not interested in anyone going to jail. I'm interested in knowing the facts what happened. I still want to know what happened.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:14.000
I want to bring some closure to this. Carolyn Bryant Donham, I understand she wanted some one of them to give her immunity. FBI said we can't give you. We're not prosecuting. We just investigate.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:27.000
Mr. the man that was on the truck with him out of Ohio trying to think of his name. His son out of New York, the end of the door.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:36.000
He understand that he wanted immunity. He said he didn't know anything about it. He wasn't there. And I can't think of his name. But anyway.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:49.000
So all of these things are happening. And I'm just kind of going with the flow. And she said they cannot find enough information to indict Carolyn Bryant Donham.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:55:04.000
Then Alvin comes with the Till Bill. That helps pursue other cases that has this place. Still not bringing the closure that I want. I want to know what happened. Carolyn Bryant Donham knows what happened.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:15.000
That's what I would love. That would do me a whole lot of good. I'm not going to bring him back. But I don't know if you understand what I'm saying. Bring closure to know is to have closure.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:27.000
And you can appreciate that. I don't want to think that happened to her. I leave the woman alone. And I doubted even if they gave him immunity, which you tell truth like it really happened to be very difficult.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:35.000
A role by our house with the Mississippi. Inversal Mississippi. Literally a retool.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:48.000
Harding carders. I was a huge from there. We fought. We did the whole. I was with a group of people I had in the business with. But I was there because of the material. I'm not a literary person.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:57.000
And don't claim that we don't try. I tried. I am who I am. But anyway, it was a very interesting and form and enlightening thing to me.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:08.000
So those are some of the feelings that I had and to meet with Eric Holden going to the (US) Justice Department. Those are great experiences, talk with the great minds.

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:16.000
But you deal with human beings. And I know I'm dealing with human beings. I know they can only go so far and only do so much.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:18.000
Did you ever meet Joyce?

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:31.000
No, I don't think so. I don't think I met Joyce. Maybe she did come to Chicago with the FBI. I can't remember. I wouldn't say for sure. I never met her down there.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:42.000
But she was courageous to do what she did. Her and her is right living in the same town. So that was quite a... I hate some questions about that.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:54.000
Because you're human. You're dealing with human beings. You're doing this and what's going to happen. People are crazy. Some people may not wrap tight.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:57:03.000
So I had some concerns about her. But anyway, she did a great job. I think she did.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:09.000
Did you have a...

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:20.000
You got a Mississippi recently as we started our conversation. But while back at the premium trail, the inaugural Mississippi Freedom Trail marker ceremony.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:25.000
Were you able to find any sense of...

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:31.000
What meaning do you find in all of this all these years later?

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:42.000
I probably found more meaning in terms of history. Telling history. And I was always like a little history buff.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:53.000
And this... It means more to me to see the children benefit from the history part of it than for me personally.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:02.000
I do it because I went... They let me know they didn't have enough money. And that's how I could pay my own way. Because I want the history to get out there.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:14.000
So I'm doing it from that perspective. I met down. There was some kids from Dominican High School. Good friend of mine, Mike Smolow. They used a par bearer at Miss Teel's Film. He was on the white par bear.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:20.000
They were there. So I feel good that I'm able to contribute.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:34.000
I don't let nobody try to make me a hero or something great because all I did was survive. Scared as I could be. No hero. I'm just survived to tell the story.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:42.000
So that's my take on it. I don't try to get any miles out of it for myself.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:50.000
I didn't do nothing. If I could have disappeared, I would have been there.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:59:02.000
And it means a lot. People are very appreciative when I come and talk. Being eyewitness, I guess I'm just learning how much it means to them.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:11.000
Because you tell it over and over and you survived it. It's something that happened that you wish had happened and it was a tragic event.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:27.000
When people want to hear the story and they want to hear the truth. Especially children. Most of them adults. They have to. They said in their ways and they have their own ideas about things. So that means a lot to me.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:36.000
John, let's pause for just a second.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:46.000
Let me ask. Let me ask you about the.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:58.000
Some of these in Mississippi here in more recent years to memorialize.

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:06.000
They also designated a stretch of highway.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:14.000
I don't know if you know the story on that coming to pass and your perspective on that.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:25.000
I think Senator Jordan had something to do with presenting that to the body.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:37.000
I was there with this ceremony just past a few days ago. I said, that's saying used to be. I thought the same was tall. It says it's been torn down a lot of times.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:49.000
Not surprised. Like I say, can't legislate the heart. Some people die heart. They're die hearts.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:59.000
This is a stretch of highway and it's good for history. Not only there, they have a marker. This is going away from the highway.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:09.000
The Tallahatchie County. I don't know you know about them. They are very much interested in the immatil story. A lot of things happen there.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:19.000
They have a marker at the spot at the riverways. The bodies will go out. They have a marker by the funeral home that had its body.

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:28.000
They have a marker at the courthouse in Sumner, Mississippi and they're trying to restore that to its original order.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:46.000
They have a marker by the barn. It's a place where they actually tore it in it. These are things that are good for history and be able to go by and identify with it.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:58.000
It means a lot to especially history concerning people. The highway and all those things have this place and some people use it and take advantage of something.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:04.000
They just really don't like it.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:16.000
So, those efforts in so far as they happen in the cases we've just described, those efforts seem to you well meaning and sincere or are the motives more complicated than them.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:30.000
I think the people who live there have a lot of, I think, fire trying to write wrongs. But you can only go so far and I appreciate what they're doing.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:44.000
I think sometimes they become frustrated because again they want to change people's heart. Those kind of things don't change hearts. Believe me they do not and they never will.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:56.000
But it's good for history. Let it do what it's supposed to do. And I hope they don't get just discouraged because they do all of this and this is the 2000 level.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:06.000
So this day and time, yeah, this day and time. And The Bible says evil men and seducers will wax worse and worse. That's revival in this country on racism.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:22.000
I mean we regress and fast, you know, but it was there all the time. It was there all the time. So I just hope they don't get too, become too wrapped up in it in the sense that they expect more than what they're going to get.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:34.000
Know where you're at. Know what you're doing. Keep doing it. Keep changing. Change is ever made and change is going to be made. It's going to go slow and just hope the God he touched people's heart.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:48.000
Well, last question. At times you speak to children school children, younger people about all of this history. Do you find that you can communicate successfully to them?

01:03:48.000 --> 01:04:00.000
The true nature of all of what that history was back then and nature in Mississippi society then. Are they able to get a hold of all of them?

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:11.000
They're much more receptive to it than the older. The older you get the less receptive you are to it from my experience of talking to people.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:27.000
I was just at the University of Missouri in Columbia, Missouri, about three weeks ago. And in the college level, you found less receptiveness than you were at eighth grade and you know, the eighth grade level.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:44.000
And one thing I point out to both of them and blacks. I say the progress and the success that black people made. There was always somebody right there to fight, start to cause.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:56.000
Otherwise, we would not be here. I say, Abraham Lincoln got a lot of criticism when he tried to handle the rest of the situation. Once he sent 500 African Americans to Haiti, he needed to go get him brother of starving.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:08.000
So what he did for the time was very noble and courageous. President Kennedy, President Johnson, signed the Civil Rights Bill.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:25.000
Then I saw them thinking the progress that we meet in all areas. The fire was in some white person's belly to stand up. Civil Rights, the freedom writers, what made it really successful is when the whites came down and joined in.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:32.000
And the white guy said, I knew I was going to be more targeted than the blacks because they're going to hate me for coming in with them.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:45.000
So I tell them, I said, look, you guys are going to be sentences or whatever you are. I said, you can make the difference. Do what's right. When white kid told him what I said, well, he said, I'm going to do what's right. I'm going to stand up. I said, you're not going to be liked.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:57.000
You're just staying too strong and you're not going to be liked. And then I want the blacks to appreciate how God touched hearts and how a lot of this came about.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:09.000
You didn't fight you way to this. That's why King was so bitter against violence because you're going to be slaughtered. So you have to realize that you got to work together.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:24.000
We stand and divided. We fall. It all seems still very much very much with us in a very present sense. And it tills case it doesn't seem it's a hard imagine even somehow that it's 56 years ago.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:36.000
Because there's so much revival. There's so much just being done. He got killed 57 years ago. But all these changes are just coming about.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:46.000
And he's still in the making. He's still here speaking for so many years. He just laid dormant. There was nothing. You hear about it here and there.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:56.000
I tell people to me it's like the sathans say, you got what he deserved. And all of a sudden all these changes come by. I mean people were interested.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:05.000
So it's so much being done. And especially when the young people are the young people are going to have to make the changes.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:13.000
They're the old people they ain't trying to change. They ain't trying to change. For the most part.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:15.000
It's been a real honor and pleasure to be with you.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:17.000
Pleasure to see you.

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:29.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
